Date: 0/0/1922
Source: Sheep Farming in NZ
Author: PERRY
Vol / Page: 83
Edition:
Quote: A boy or man to five shearers is sufficient for picking up the fleeces, but the operations at the wool table will be described in the chapter on wool-classing... <i>Ibid.</i> 119  The farmer should be careful to distinguish between `wool classing' and `wool sorting'. Wool sorting is a process employed in manufacture, ... In wool classing groups of qualities are dealt with, generally representing the fine and coarse wools of a flock, and lines are made according to condition (i.e. amount of grease), soundness, and length of staple, ... <i>Wool classing</i> is the placing of <i>whole</i> fleeces, after skirting, into different classes or grades according to the condition, quality, and strength and length of fibre
